 <h1>{{ page.title }}</h1>
	<p> 
	Welcome to the website of the Kleine seminar! This small seminar takes place at Universiteit Gent and was initiated in summer 2019 to create a space 
	for graduate students and postdoc researchers with shared research interests to study recent subject in depth. The method is quite simple:
	each semester, the members meet and decide of one subject they want to investigate, then they choose a base reference and divide the subject amongst
	themselves so that each of them will present a part. It aims to keep an informal ambiance and every kind of questions is welcomed, especially 
	<a href="https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/ask-yourself-dumb-questions-and-answer-them/">dumb ones</a>! 
	</p>


	<h4>Next meeting: Friday 03rd December 13:15 to 14:15, Michiel Smet</h4>
	
	<p> 
	Michiel will present Chapter 6.
	</p>
			
	
<h4>Resources for the seminar</h4>
<p> 

Etingof, Gelaki, Nikshych and Ostrik have written recently a book on tensor categories (see <a href="https://pages.uoregon.edu/vostrik/">https://pages.uoregon.edu/vostrik/</a> and navigate to the book).
		In the preface, they outline a possible one-semester course that we could do to cover this exciting material. Here is it with minor touch
<table>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 1</td><td>Homework and brief recap (1.1 to 1.9)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 2</td><td>2.1 to 2.10</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 3</td><td>Skip unless needed</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 4</td><td>4.1 to 4.9</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 5</td><td>5.1 to 5.6, more if wanted</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 6</td><td>6.1 to 6.3</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 7</td><td>7.1 to 7.12</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 8</td><td>8.1 to 8.14</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chapter 9</td><td>9.1 to 9.9 with 9.12</td>
</tr>
</table>

Do not hesitate to use other sources such as Deligne's work, Mac Lane, Etingof and Ostrik, Joyal or Drinfeld etc.
</p>
	
	
